Q.1.1¶

An Exchange-Traded Fund (ETF) is an investment fund that holds assets such as stocks, commodities, bonds, or foreign currency. An ETF is traded like a stock throughout the trading day at fluctuating prices. They often track indexes. There are many types of Exchange-Traded Funds. Some of the most common ETFs include Stocks, Index, Bonds, Currency, Invese ETF, Actively Managed, Leveraged and Real Estate ETF

#Q 1.2 Calculate average of a specific fund using purely python and NOT pandas
# importing csv module
import csv
import random


# csv file name
file = open("/Users/monika/Documents/WQUMSC/ML in Finance/M3/MScFE 650 MLF GWP Data.csv", 'r') 
# creating dictreader object
file = csv.DictReader(file)
# craeting empty lists
List1= []
# iterating over each row and append
# values to empty list
for col in file:
  List1.append(col['MSCI ARGENTINA'])
my_list = [float(i) for i in List1]
print(my_list)
rand = []
for i in range(len(my_list)):
  rand.append(random.uniform(0, 1))

print(*List1, sep='\n')

# Q4.1 Write a Python function that graphs 1 time series with appropriate time labels
# Plot 1 time series
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
def plot_series(series_data):
    series_data.plot(figsize=(15,10), linewidth=5, fontsize=20)
    plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=20)
    
plot_series(data[['LUXXX']])
In [45]:
# Q4.2 Write a Python function that graphs 2 time series on the same plot, with labels
#Concatenate together both series and plot them

def plot_two_series(X, Y):
    data_rm = pd.concat([X, Y], axis=1)
    data_rm.plot(figsize=(20,10), linewidth=5, fontsize=20)
    plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=20)
    plt.ylabel('Fields value', fontsize=20)
    plt.title("Time Series", size=20)
plot_two_series(data[['LUXXX']], data[['MSCI USA']])
In [46]:
#Q4.3 Write a Python function that compares the 2 return series
def plot_diff_series(data_rm):
    data_rm.diff().plot(figsize=(20,10), linewidth=5, fontsize=20)
    plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=20);
    plt.ylabel('Fields value', fontsize=20);
    plt.title("First-order differences", size=20)
    
plot_diff_series(data_rm)

Q7.4 What is your interpretation of the 1st component?
Ans: From the first component certain cluster of fund value can be clearly described by the initial weeks of the calendar year having high(positive values) from PCA1 column in the above table.

Q 8.1 & 8.2 Common and difference in PCA and lasso
Ans: PCA can be used as a dimensionality reduction technique if you drop Principal Components based on a heuristic, but it offers no feature selection, as the Principal Components are retained instead of the original features. However, tuning the number of Principal Components retained should work better than using heuristics, unless there are many low variance components and you are simply interested in filtering them.


LASSO (ℓ1 regularization) on the other hand can, intrinsically, perform feature selection as the coefficients of predictors are shrunk towards zero. It still requires hyperparameter tuning because there's a regularization coefficient that weights how severe is the regularization of the loss function.

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline

# Principal components regression (PCA)
steps = [
    ('scale', StandardScaler()),
    ('pca', PCA()),
    ('estimator', LinearRegression())
]
pipe = Pipeline(steps)
pca = pipe.set_params(pca__n_components=10)
pca.fit(X, y)

# Q 10.1 to Q 10.5- 

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression 
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import Lasso
from scipy.stats import uniform
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")

# Split the data into testing and training, with 2/3 for training and 1/3 for testing

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, train_size=2/3, test_size=1/3)
alpha_lasso = [(i+1)/1000 for i in range(1000)]
alpha_num = 1000
pred_num = X.shape[1]
coeff_a = np.zeros((alpha_num, pred_num))
train_r_squared = np.zeros(alpha_num)
test_r_squared = np.zeros(alpha_num)

# For the lasso, use at least 1000 different values of the penalty parameter


for i in range(1000):    
    reg = Lasso(alpha = alpha_lasso[i])
    reg.fit(X_train, y_train)
    coeff_a[i,:] = reg.coef_
    train_r_squared[i] = reg.score(X_train, y_train)
    test_r_squared[i] = reg.score(X_test, y_test)
    
#prin the( train_r_squared)
# Graph the overall model mismatch for each of the 1000 values of the paramter

plt.plot(train_r_squared, 'bo-', label=r'$R^2$ Training set', color="darkgreen", alpha=0.6, linewidth=3)
plt.plot(test_r_squared, 'bo-', label=r'$R^2$ Test set', color="darkred", alpha=0.6, linewidth=3)
plt.xlabel('alpha index'); plt.ylabel(r'$R^2$')
plt.title(r'Evaluate lasso regression with 1000 alphas')
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.grid()
